<p>The materials in this collection may be protected by copyright law (U.S. Code: Title 17). Any use of the material which exceeds fair use requires permission from the copyright holder. Researchers are solely responsible for obtaining the proper permission(s) for their use of the material.</p>  </userestrict>
  <altformavail id="aspace_76e3fd2bbdbfcccade6a1c9de0b16bf7">
    <head>Existence and Location of Copies</head>
<p>The correspondence in the collection has been digitized and can be accessed at: http://mdid3.hartford.edu. Access to the digital repository is limited to the University of Hartford Campus.</p>  </altformavail>
  <bioghist id="aspace_9131ec5e17e7697afd970ad9b3638434">
    <head>Biographical / Historical</head>
<p>Harold Bauer, world renowned concert pianist, was a long-time teacher and supporter of the Hartt School, He was closely associated with its early development and founders.</p>  </bioghist>
  <otherfindaid id="aspace_caa831e7f0bdb3e58bbcd379e6a3e041">
    <head>Other Finding Aids</head>
<p>An incomplete general index (arch1710461) and subject index (arch1710462) to the correspondence in the collection (which includes summaries of letters), can be found in the digital repository by their identifiers at: http://mdid3.hartford.edu. Public access to the digital repository is limited to the University of Hartford Campus. Students, faculty, and staff can login anywhere with their university email and password.</p>  </otherfindaid>
  <scopecontent id="aspace_4986194f51b9f4d4281a88168958bdda">
    <head>Scope and Contents</head>
<p>The collection consists primarily of correspondence and photographs from 1900-1956, with the bulk of the collection dating from 1928-1951. The correspondence is mostly between Harold Bauer and Moshe Paranov. The photographs  are primarily portraits and group photographs of his master classes, but also includes a few photographs of Bauer with members of the Julius Hartt School of Music.</p>  </scopecontent>
